-- #561 PR-A (native) — the GENUINE-VALUE-CYCLE that only LAZINESS can answer, now
-- FIXED on the NATIVE backend and serving as a REGRESSION LOCK (acceptance repro #5).
--
-- `x = x + 1` is a non-productive cyclic value: `x` depends on `x`. A topo sort has NO
-- correct order for it (that is why #553 Stage B deliberately left it open). eval — the
-- reference engine implementing the DECIDED lazy-nullary semantics — black-holes the
-- cell and raises E-CYCLIC-VALUE (exit 1). #561 PR-A makes native match: a top-level
-- nullary global reaching a cycle is emitted LAZILY (@mdk_force_x + an @mdk_gs_x state
-- flag), and re-entering the still-FORCING cell calls @mdk_cyclic_value → the same coded
-- E-CYCLIC-VALUE, exit 1, EMPTY stdout.
--
-- The golden is EMPTY (this harness diffs STDOUT; the error goes to stderr). Before PR-A
-- native EAGER-initialised `x`'s cell to 0, computed `0 + 1`, and printed `1` at exit 0 —
-- a silent wrong answer. If native regresses to eager init, this fixture prints `1` and
-- fails. Do NOT delete it, and do NOT restore the `1` golden.
--
-- ⚠️ WASM IS STILL A GAP until #561 PR-B: wasm's ref-mode eager init leaves the cell null
-- and prints nothing (empty stdout, trap, exit 1). So native and wasm now COINCIDE on
-- empty stdout (nw=eq) but for different reasons; eval errors (its arm is `na`). The
-- engines ledger row (test/engine_divergence.txt) records `na:eq:na:na:ran:ran` and stays
-- ledgered until PR-B makes wasm raise E-CYCLIC-VALUE too and the row fully drains.
--
-- Measured on the shipping engines after PR-A (2026-07-18):
--   eval   -> runtime error [E-CYCLIC-VALUE], exit 1, empty stdout   (correct)
--   native -> runtime error [E-CYCLIC-VALUE], exit 1, empty stdout   (FIXED — was `1`)
--   wasm   -> instantiate trap, exit 1, empty stdout                 (PR-B gap)

x = x + 1

main = x
